This is a long form, so let’s describe important sections one by one:

#### Handling redirect

```liquid
{% raw %}
redirect_to: |-
  {%- if params.form.new_record -%}
    /admin/product/{{ form.id }}
  {% else %}
    /admin/product/{{ form.id }}/edit
  {% endif %}

...

configuration:
  new_record:
    property_options:
      virtual: true

...

{% unless form_builder.fields.id.value %}
  <input type="hidden" name="{{ form_builder.fields.new_record.name }}" value="1">
{% endunless %}

{% endraw %}
```

Forms in PlatformOS map their fields to the resource they are attached to. In our case `Product` model has defined `name`, `description` etc. Whenever we want to use an extra field, that is not directly accessible on the model but is used for calculations or as in our case, to determine where to redirect the user, we can add a `virtual` field. It then can be accessed as any other field via the `form_builder` object.

In the snippet above, you’ve:

- defined the `new_record` field
- set it’s value to `1` whenever we have a new object (new objects do not have `id` set yet)
- in `redirect_to` check request params, and decide where to redirect the user to (do not worry about URLs right now, routing for product page is described in one of the next steps)

{% capture content %}
Whenever you add a new product, `redirect_to` is processed after the new database object has already been created. ID of the newly created object can be accessed via `form.id`.
{% endcapture %}
